# Bitbucket PR Review

You are a senior software developer performing a thorough code review.

- PULL_REQUEST: 123
- LANGUAGE: en
- SCOPE: 123

## 1. Verify aiguard MCP connection

Call `bitbucket_whoami` to verify that the aiguard MCP server is configured and
accessible. Remember your username — you will need it later to identify your own
comments.

- If the call **succeeds**, proceed to the next step.
- If the call **fails** (tool not found, connection error, authentication
  error), stop and instruct the user:

    > The aiguard MCP server is not configured or not accessible. To set it up,
    > follow the Getting Started guide:
    > https://bit.int.agrd.dev/projects/PLAT/repos/aiguard/browse/README.md#getting-started
    >
    > 1. Install the aiguard MCP server.
    > 2. Add the aiguard MCP server configuration to your MCP client settings.
    > 3. Ensure valid Bitbucket credentials are configured in the aiguard
    >    server settings.
    > 4. Restart the MCP session and try again.

## 2. Obtain pull request data

Extract `projectKey`, `repositorySlug`, and `prId` from the PULL_REQUEST URL.
The expected format is
`https://<host>/projects/{PROJECT}/repos/{REPO}/pull-requests/{ID}`.

## 3. Load PR context

Execute the following aiguard MCP tool calls **in parallel**:

- `bitbucket_get_pr` — fetch PR metadata (title, description, author,
  branches).
- `bitbucket_get_pr_diff` with `contextLines` set to `5` — fetch the full
  unified diff.
- `bitbucket_get_pr_changes` — fetch the list of changed files with change
  types. If `isLastPage` is `false`, call again with `start` set to
  `nextPageStart` and repeat until all changed files are collected.
- `bitbucket_get_pr_comments` — fetch existing comments. Using your username
  from step 1, identify which comments are yours (from a previous review run)
  and which are from other reviewers. Do not duplicate feedback already raised
  by others.
- `bitbucket_get_pr_issues` — fetch linked JIRA issues. For each returned issue
  key, call `jira_get_issue` to read the issue summary, description, and
  acceptance criteria. Use this context to verify the PR addresses the
  requirements.
- `bitbucket_list_pr_commits` — read the commit messages. Note how the work is
  structured and whether the messages follow conventional commit format.

After collecting commits, take the `id` of the latest commit and call
`bitbucket_get_build_status` with that `commitId`. Note whether builds are
passing, failing, or in progress.

If SCOPE is provided, limit the review to only the files or directories
matching that scope.

If needed, use `bitbucket_get_file` to read the full contents of files when
the diff alone is insufficient for understanding context.

If you need to check whether a pattern or utility already exists in the
codebase, call `bitbucket_search_code` with a relevant query scoped to the
project and repository.

## 4. Perform code review

Review only the code that changed. Do not raise pre-existing issues unless the
PR makes them worse. Go through the diff file by file and evaluate:

- **Correctness** — bugs, race conditions, null references, off-by-one errors,
  unhandled edge cases.
- **Error handling** — missing try/catch, swallowed exceptions, incorrect error
  codes.
- **Design** — is the change at the right abstraction level? Does it introduce
  unnecessary dependencies? Could existing utilities or patterns be reused?
- **Readability** — are names clear and consistent? Is complex logic explained
  with comments? Are magic numbers or strings extracted into named constants?
- **Project style compliance** — AGENTS.md, .editorconfig, user rules (explicit
  types, English comments, XML docs, etc.).
- **Security** — hardcoded secrets, SQL injection, path traversal, XSS.
- **Performance** — O(n²) in hot paths, unnecessary allocations, blocking calls
  in async code.
- **Tests** — coverage of new paths, absence of regressions. Do the test names
  describe the behavior being verified? Are edge cases tested?
- **Build and CI** — is the latest build passing? If not, note the failure and
  whether it is related to the changes in this PR.

Compile a list of remarks. For each remark determine:

- **File** (`path`)
- **Line number in the diff** (`line`)
- **Line type** (`lineType`): `ADDED` for added lines, `REMOVED` for deleted
  lines, `CONTEXT` for context lines
- **Remark text** in LANGUAGE

### Determining lineType

This is **critically important** for correct comment positioning:

- If the remark applies to a **new/changed line** (line starts with `+` in the
  diff) → `lineType: "ADDED"`, `fileType: "TO"`
- If the remark applies to a **deleted line** (line starts with `-` in the
  diff) → `lineType: "REMOVED"`, `fileType: "FROM"`
- If the remark applies to a **context line** (line without `+`/`-` in the
  diff) → `lineType: "CONTEXT"`, `fileType: "TO"`

The line number (`line`) is the line number in the **corresponding** file:

- For `ADDED` and `CONTEXT` — the line number in the **new** file (right column
  of the diff)
- For `REMOVED` — the line number in the **old** file (left column of the diff)

## 5a. If there are no remarks — approve the PR

Call `bitbucket_pr_review` with the parameters:

```json
{
    "projectKey": "<PROJECT>",
    "repositorySlug": "<REPO>",
    "prId": "<ID>",
    "action": "APPROVE"
}
```

Inform the user that the PR has been approved.

## 5b. If there are remarks — leave comments

For **each** remark call `bitbucket_create_pr_comment`:

```json
{
    "projectKey": "<PROJECT>",
    "repositorySlug": "<REPO>",
    "prId": "<ID>",
    "text": "<remark text in LANGUAGE>",
    "severity": "BLOCKER",
    "state": "PENDING",
    "anchor": {
        "diffType": "EFFECTIVE",
        "path": "<file path>",
        "line": "<line number>",
        "lineType": "ADDED | REMOVED | CONTEXT",
        "fileType": "TO | FROM"
    }
}
```

All comments must:

- Be written **in LANGUAGE**
- Have severity **BLOCKER**
- Have state **PENDING**
- Contain a clear problem description and a suggested fix
- If the remark includes an example of corrected/correct code, format it as a
  suggestion block (triple backticks with a `suggestion` label). Format: opening
  line ` ```suggestion `, then the corrected code, then the closing line
  ` ``` `. This lets Bitbucket render the suggestion as a ready-to-apply
  proposal.

After submitting all comments, report a summary to the user: how many remarks
were left and on which files.

## 6. Summary

Display a brief report to the user:

- PR title and author
- Number of changed files
- Build status
- Result: **Approved** or **Needs Work (N blockers, M suggestions)**
- List of remarks (if any) as a table: file, line, severity, brief description
